</table>
<p><b>Roadrunner</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Supercomputer" title="Supercomputer">supercomputer</a> built by <a href="/wiki/IBM" title="IBM">IBM</a> at the <a href="/wiki/Los_Alamos_National_Laboratory" title="Los Alamos National Laboratory">Los Alamos National Laboratory</a> in <a href="/wiki/New_Mexico" title="New Mexico">New Mexico</a>, USA. Currently the world's fastest computer, the US$133-million Roadrunner is designed for a peak performance of 1.7 <a href="/wiki/FLOPS" title="FLOPS">petaflops</a>, achieving 1.026 on May 25, 2008,<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> and to be the world's first <a href="/wiki/TOP500" title="TOP500">TOP500</a> <a href="/wiki/LINPACK" title="LINPACK">Linpack</a> sustained 1.0 petaflops system. It is a one-of-a-kind supercomputer, built from commodity parts, with many novel design features.</p>
